WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:00.300
Okay.

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.460
Welcome to our session on the pathobiology of sarcomas.

3
00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:07.340
I wanted to remind you a couple things.

4
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.920
We're going to have a webinar that will be sort of covering our

5
00:00:11.960 --> 00:00:15.440
session, so all the questions should be made in the microphones.

6
00:00:15.480 --> 00:00:19.340
That will be important. We're going to try to allow as much time for questions

7
00:00:19.420 --> 00:00:22.500
as we can. The presentations will be 20 minutes, followed by 10 minutes of

8
00:00:22.580 --> 00:00:26.540
questions, and we'll try, obviously, to give you

9
00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:30.500
an opportunity. Of course, after the session, feel free to talk to any of

10
00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:32.820
the speakers. I'm very excited about this.

11
00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:35.860
We have a good program for you guys, and

12
00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:41.200
we feel like it's a good moment to review some of the

13
00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:44.940
technologies that are coming aboard and how we think about sarcomas,

14
00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:48.160
hopefully increasingly in more systematic ways.

15
00:00:48.340 --> 00:00:52.200
And we'll try to cover the idea of going from bench to bedside, using

16
00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:55.900
some new molecular biology approaches to look at chromatin in sarcomas,

17
00:00:56.320 --> 00:01:00.300
and also monitoring disease. So without further ado, our first

18
00:01:00.340 --> 00:01:03.820
speaker is Brian Rubin from the Cleveland Clinic, and

19
00:01:04.360 --> 00:01:06.920
he will be talking about bench to bedside in EHE.

20
00:01:14.600 --> 00:01:16.300
Okay. Thanks very much, Miguel,

21
00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:21.280
and thanks for organizing this, and thanks to all of you for finding this room.

22
00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:25.980
I know that was probably a little bit of a trick. So, yeah.

23
00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:29.170
I'm a pathologist. I'm going to talk a little bit

24
00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:33.060
about just a really brief introduction to where we are with sarcoma

25
00:01:33.260 --> 00:01:37.180
in terms of diagnosis and how I think genetics has really been

26
00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:40.600
the game changer for us. It's been unbelievable the amount of genetic information,

27
00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:44.040
and I'll show you a very dramatic slide kind of summarizing that in a moment.

28
00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:47.580
But I work on something called epithelioid hemangioendothelioma, which is a rare

29
00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:50.440
vascular tumor, and we'll talk about that largely.

30
00:01:51.040 --> 00:01:55.020
So, I got a few slides from-- These are the slides from a talk I used

31
00:01:55.060 --> 00:01:58.480
to give to residents about 30 years ago when I first started in this field.

32
00:01:59.160 --> 00:01:59.680
And

33
00:02:00.520 --> 00:02:04.280
we've traditionally classified sarcomas by their line of differentiation.

34
00:02:04.400 --> 00:02:07.340
So if they're osteosarcomas, they make some sort of bony matrix.

35
00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:10.241
Chondrosarcoma makes cartilage, et cetera.

36
00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:13.300
Some of the things that we work on in sarcoma, like synovial sarcoma, Ewing

37
00:02:13.340 --> 00:02:17.230
sarcoma, we still don't really understand the line of differentiation or the

38
00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:21.300
cell of origin, or much about it, and that has to do with we've really kind of

39
00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:24.760
lagged in the understanding of mesenchymal stem cell biology.

40
00:02:25.320 --> 00:02:28.800
As it catches up, I think we'll learn more, and it'll be really insightful in our

41
00:02:28.820 --> 00:02:30.560
understanding of sarcomas.

42
00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:36.380
I always show this slide. So this was a slice through a patient's leg,

43
00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:38.060
actually from an amputation specimen.

44
00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:41.820
And really the extremities are the major sites, extremities and chest wall for

45
00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:45.840
sarcoma development. You can see with all the different things, skin,

46
00:02:46.020 --> 00:02:47.020
fat, bone,

47
00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:51.989
et cetera. All the precursors, presumably, to give rise to these

48
00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:55.350
cancers are living in the extremities, and that's why they're so common there, but

49
00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.290
I just show it there dramatically.

50
00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:00.900
And again, synovial sarcoma and Ewing sarcoma are unusual because they can

51
00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:04.460
arise anywhere in the body, probably presumably from some sort of

52
00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:08.120
primitive circulating stem cells that aren't located, for instance, in a

53
00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:12.220
leg or wherever. And the way that we

54
00:03:12.260 --> 00:03:16.060
traditionally classified when I was coming up as a resident, we used histology.

55
00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:19.680
So we looked through microscopes, much as Virchow did for over 100

56
00:03:19.780 --> 00:03:22.820
years, and tried to get a pretty good idea of what we're looking at.

57
00:03:23.340 --> 00:03:27.280
Ultrastructure was pretty big back when I trained back in the '90s.

58
00:03:27.640 --> 00:03:31.140
The Ultrastructural Pathology Society used to be a huge meeting at the

59
00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:34.360
USCAP. Nowadays, you go and it's just a bunch of renal

60
00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:37.769
pathologists. So ultrastructure has largely disappeared from the role

61
00:03:37.769 --> 00:03:41.740
of diagnosing sarcoma. And then immunohistochemical studies

62
00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.359
came up, and so we were using a lot of immunohistochemistry.

63
00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:49.760
Now genetics. So, I trained back and I started my training in

64
00:03:49.769 --> 00:03:50.640
'95.

65
00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:52.660
We had translocations

66
00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:56.760
that we were looking at, and there was a variety of translocations that were

67
00:03:56.780 --> 00:04:00.140
specific for a variety of cancers.

68
00:04:00.170 --> 00:04:03.180
And you can see here, this is kind of what we had at the time being.

69
00:04:03.220 --> 00:04:06.720
Here's some of the translocations of something like extraskeletal myxoid

70
00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:09.260
chondrosarcoma we knew was a 9;22 translocation.

71
00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:09.800
So,

72
00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:14.760
the cytogenetics has played a very key role in sort

73
00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:17.981
of early understanding. We knew for things like

74
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.820
dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans, they had ring chromosomes composed of chromosomes

75
00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:25.800
17 and 22, but this was really the extent of

76
00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:26.620
our knowledge.

77
00:04:28.180 --> 00:04:31.360
So now this is circa 2024,

78
00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:34.960
and this is what we know about the genetics of sarcoma.

79
00:04:34.969 --> 00:04:38.330
And so all these gene fusions have been cloned. I cloned a couple of them.

80
00:04:38.340 --> 00:04:38.440
I was

81
00:04:39.400 --> 00:04:42.760
lucky enough to clone a couple in my career and identify their genetic

82
00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:46.580
alterations. But you can see there's mostly

83
00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:51.020
gene fusions that are involving transcription factors.

84
00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:53.600
There's some kinases, there's epigenetic regulators.

85
00:04:53.620 --> 00:04:56.920
So we're really seeing the complete kind of picture here, and this is really due to

86
00:04:56.940 --> 00:04:58.330
developments in things like

87
00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:01.740
NGS, the Archer gene fusion panel.

88
00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:05.500
I don't know if people know about that, but it's a way essentially of

89
00:05:05.560 --> 00:05:07.700
PCRing using NGS

90
00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:11.980
in a multiplex way, a variety of primers.

91
00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:15.800
And John Ifrady's sitting here in the audience, who's really the guy who

92
00:05:15.860 --> 00:05:19.660
created the tech behind the Archer gene fusion panel,

93
00:05:19.700 --> 00:05:23.430
and we're still every week discovering a new gene fusion in my

94
00:05:23.460 --> 00:05:26.700
group. We don't know what they mean most of the time, and we're going to move to

95
00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:30.660
RNA-seq probably in the near future, and that will even just bombard us with

96
00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:32.620
further information. But at this point,

97
00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:36.980
this is what we're dealing with. It's a lot of genetic complexity, but it has

98
00:05:37.040 --> 00:05:40.969
taught us a lot about classification of sarcoma, and

99
00:05:40.969 --> 00:05:44.950
that's allowed us to feed information to oncologists to help

100
00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:48.460
them treat and whatnot. And actually, we learned a lot about the biology.

101
00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:53.000
So just to impress upon you, for me, the big game changer has just been

102
00:05:53.100 --> 00:05:57.050
NGS and all of what we've learned from the variations of using

103
00:05:57.140 --> 00:05:57.680
NGS.

104
00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:01.200
So now I'm going to move on and talk a bit about EHE.

105
00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:01.560
So,

106
00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:05.020
epithelioid hemangioendothelioma is the full name.

107
00:06:05.060 --> 00:06:06.880
For obvious reasons, I'm not going to keep saying

108
00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:10.808
that.It's an ultra-rare sarcoma, so it actually

109
00:06:10.848 --> 00:06:14.058
falls into the ultra-rare group. There's about 200 new cases in the United States

110
00:06:14.108 --> 00:06:14.698
each year. There's

111
00:06:15.948 --> 00:06:19.548
about 1,000 patients at any one time that have it in the United States because

112
00:06:19.588 --> 00:06:23.468
they can live for a while. So we've got a wide age range with a peak in

113
00:06:23.488 --> 00:06:24.928
middle age. It does occur in kids.

114
00:06:25.748 --> 00:06:29.528
Arises in skin, soft tissue, bone, visceral organs.

115
00:06:31.108 --> 00:06:34.888
And there are no standard treatment options for this disease, as there are for

116
00:06:34.928 --> 00:06:38.478
many sarcomas. So on that last panel, we saw most of those

117
00:06:38.548 --> 00:06:42.448
are chimeric transcription factors, and we just really haven't

118
00:06:42.508 --> 00:06:45.908
figured out a good way to have a game plan now to

119
00:06:46.908 --> 00:06:50.048
impact a chimeric transcription factor. Those targets are very obvious.

120
00:06:50.128 --> 00:06:52.588
Treating them is an entirely different story.

121
00:06:52.668 --> 00:06:56.268
The five-year disease-specific mortality depends on the location.

122
00:06:56.348 --> 00:06:57.888
Soft tissue has the best prognosis.

123
00:06:58.508 --> 00:07:01.568
Lung has the worst prognosis, especially pleural disease.

124
00:07:01.648 --> 00:07:04.608
Once EHE involves the pleura or

125
00:07:05.808 --> 00:07:09.668
the peritoneal surfaces, the patients have about a six-month survival time,

126
00:07:09.888 --> 00:07:10.948
median of six months.

127
00:07:13.048 --> 00:07:15.708
So this was built sort of as a pathology section.

128
00:07:17.628 --> 00:07:21.038
So I did bring a few slides. I'll explain them to you if you're not a pathologist,

129
00:07:21.068 --> 00:07:22.908
and I know that probably some of you aren't.

130
00:07:22.948 --> 00:07:26.428
This is actually a liver with EHE in it, and it has a way of being vasocentric.

131
00:07:26.468 --> 00:07:30.408
That's a blood vessel in the middle, and you can see it's stuffed with EHE.

132
00:07:30.528 --> 00:07:32.148
Over on the right, here's what they look like.

133
00:07:32.208 --> 00:07:34.328
And so what you can see here is

134
00:07:35.868 --> 00:07:38.548
that there's a monotonous proliferation of these small cells.

135
00:07:38.848 --> 00:07:42.668
They don't look very angry or outwardly malignant, and they're

136
00:07:42.708 --> 00:07:45.748
set in this really abundant myxofibrillary kind of

137
00:07:45.848 --> 00:07:49.778
stroma. Our lab actually spends a lot of time studying that

138
00:07:49.788 --> 00:07:51.628
stroma, but I'm not going to talk about that today.

139
00:07:51.708 --> 00:07:54.928
Now, they do stain for vascular markers, so here's CD31, which is a very good

140
00:07:54.988 --> 00:07:58.548
endothelial marker, and then ERG on this side, which is also a good

141
00:07:58.608 --> 00:07:59.608
endothelial marker.

142
00:08:01.518 --> 00:08:05.158
Now, I got really interested in this disease because it had a translocation, and I

143
00:08:05.188 --> 00:08:07.508
kind of liked cloning translocations.

144
00:08:07.948 --> 00:08:09.928
And so this is a 1;3 translocation.

145
00:08:09.948 --> 00:08:12.548
It involves the short arm of 1 and the long arm of chromosome 3.

146
00:08:13.128 --> 00:08:16.888
And we didn't know what that was, but back in 2011, inspired by the work of

147
00:08:16.947 --> 00:08:20.508
Arul Chinnaiyan, who was at that time using RNA-seq to just

148
00:08:20.528 --> 00:08:23.888
sequence tumors, and then he would use bioinformatics to clone them out.

149
00:08:23.948 --> 00:08:27.158
We were the first guys who said, "Well, we've got a translocation, so we know where

150
00:08:27.208 --> 00:08:31.108
the fusion is." We just sequenced one tumor, and we got

151
00:08:31.168 --> 00:08:34.708
the fusion in about a week. We'd actually been working on it for about two years at

152
00:08:34.749 --> 00:08:38.718
that point using FISH walking and FISH mapping and shortcutted the whole process

153
00:08:38.728 --> 00:08:41.928
using NGS. So it has this thing called a TAZ CAMTA1 fusion.

154
00:08:41.968 --> 00:08:45.928
I'll talk a little bit about TAZ, but essentially TAZ CAMTA1 is a dysregulated form

155
00:08:45.968 --> 00:08:46.588
of TAZ.

156
00:08:47.528 --> 00:08:50.028
And over on the right side here, we just have some protein structures.

157
00:08:50.048 --> 00:08:53.708
And really for the purposes of this talk, what's really important is that the TID

158
00:08:53.768 --> 00:08:55.688
binding site of TAZ

159
00:08:57.188 --> 00:09:01.048
is fused essentially to most of CAMTA1, but it retains that

160
00:09:01.068 --> 00:09:04.588
TID binding site. That's a very critical interaction that

161
00:09:04.708 --> 00:09:08.128
strategically everybody that's interested in drugging this

162
00:09:08.168 --> 00:09:12.148
compound, either TAZ, YAP, or TAZ CAMTA1, is

163
00:09:12.208 --> 00:09:16.128
trying to interfere with the interaction between TID and TAZ

164
00:09:16.548 --> 00:09:17.088
or YAP.

165
00:09:18.628 --> 00:09:22.468
Now, one of the things that's kind of interesting that's like a translation of

166
00:09:22.488 --> 00:09:24.128
genetics now is we have what we call...

167
00:09:24.868 --> 00:09:27.688
This is a term coined by my friend Jason Hornick.

168
00:09:27.968 --> 00:09:30.088
He calls them next generation antibodies.

169
00:09:30.438 --> 00:09:33.928
So here what we've got is a case of EHE on the left, and on the right

170
00:09:34.368 --> 00:09:38.188
is a CAMTA1 antibody. CAMTA1 really isn't expressed at all in adult

171
00:09:38.248 --> 00:09:41.968
tissues. A little bit in neuronal tissues, but really it's not expressed very

172
00:09:42.028 --> 00:09:44.908
well. And so in any kind of cancer, if it stains for

173
00:09:44.948 --> 00:09:48.938
CAMTA1, it is syniquannon for having the gene fusion.

174
00:09:49.728 --> 00:09:53.668
And so we use CAMTA1 immunohistochemistry quite a bit to identify cases of

175
00:09:53.748 --> 00:09:54.327
EHE

176
00:09:55.268 --> 00:09:59.107
when we see them, and it has a nuclear stain, a little bit of cytoplasmic blushing

177
00:09:59.148 --> 00:09:59.628
as well.

178
00:10:02.428 --> 00:10:06.208
So here's the Hippo pathway. So the reason I'm talking about the Hippo pathway, now

179
00:10:06.268 --> 00:10:08.248
I hope I'm not jerking around too much.

180
00:10:08.268 --> 00:10:12.088
I'm trying to pile actually quite a few little stories into this

181
00:10:12.408 --> 00:10:13.508
talk, is

182
00:10:15.288 --> 00:10:18.988
that TAZ is the end effector of the Hippo pathway. So is YAP.

183
00:10:19.428 --> 00:10:23.048
So down here we have TAZ, which lives in the cytoplasm and then migrates into the

184
00:10:23.088 --> 00:10:24.868
nucleus where it acts as a transcription factor.

185
00:10:24.888 --> 00:10:26.267
It's a transcriptional co-regulator.

186
00:10:26.308 --> 00:10:30.128
It has to bind TID, and it's controlled by cell size

187
00:10:30.168 --> 00:10:32.208
and cell shape. Those are the inputs.

188
00:10:32.308 --> 00:10:36.298
They modify these serine/threonine kinases here, MST1/2 and

189
00:10:36.348 --> 00:10:38.618
LATS1/2. LATS will phosphorylate TAZ.

190
00:10:38.688 --> 00:10:40.748
If it's phosphorylated, it keeps it in the cytoplasm.

191
00:10:40.778 --> 00:10:42.608
It's a tumor-suppressive pathway.

192
00:10:42.948 --> 00:10:46.408
However, if it's unphosphorylated, it allows it to go into the nucleus where it

193
00:10:46.448 --> 00:10:49.908
binds TID, and then it has a transcriptional program, which is very

194
00:10:49.948 --> 00:10:50.978
pro-oncogenic.

195
00:10:51.978 --> 00:10:55.268
So that interaction between TAZ and TID, I will emphasize again, is kind of

196
00:10:55.308 --> 00:10:59.268
important. So when we cloned the gene fusion, there were no models.

197
00:10:59.408 --> 00:11:01.308
I work in rare cancers. There's never any models.

198
00:11:01.338 --> 00:11:02.568
We have to develop everything ourself.

199
00:11:02.608 --> 00:11:06.378
All the models, tools, are all developed by the few people who actually study these

200
00:11:06.388 --> 00:11:09.708
things. And so what we did was we expressed the gene fusion in

201
00:11:09.768 --> 00:11:13.708
NIH3T3 cells. They grew as colonies in soft agar, which gave us

202
00:11:13.748 --> 00:11:15.908
an assay, essentially, to start interrogating.

203
00:11:16.388 --> 00:11:20.048
The first thing that we looked at, because we wanted to target TAZ CAMTA1, but of

204
00:11:20.088 --> 00:11:22.148
course, that's easier said than done.

205
00:11:22.208 --> 00:11:25.278
It takes a whole chemical program, and I'll show you a little bit about how we're

206
00:11:25.308 --> 00:11:27.328
approaching that during this talk.

207
00:11:28.128 --> 00:11:31.788
But essentially, we just looked to see what signal transduction pathways were being

208
00:11:31.948 --> 00:11:35.728
activated. And what we found was that the MAP kinase pathway was

209
00:11:35.768 --> 00:11:37.668
being activated more than the

210
00:11:38.828 --> 00:11:41.108
PI3 kinase pathway. And you can see that here.

211
00:11:41.188 --> 00:11:45.008
GDC-0941 is an inhibitor of PI3K, and it really doesn't

212
00:11:45.048 --> 00:11:46.708
inhibit colony formation very well.

213
00:11:47.188 --> 00:11:50.788
But PD325901 is a tool compound for the MAP

214
00:11:50.808 --> 00:11:54.488
kinase pathway. It's a MEK inhibitor, and it has a dramatic

215
00:11:54.548 --> 00:11:57.208
effect. It actually has an IC50 below 100 nanomolars.

216
00:11:57.828 --> 00:12:01.528
Believe it or not, based on this data, almost exclusively, we did a clinical

217
00:12:01.588 --> 00:12:03.928
trial in this disease.

218
00:12:05.548 --> 00:12:06.588
Let me show you one more slide first.

219
00:12:06.648 --> 00:12:09.308
So again, you can see we actually looked at trametinib, which

220
00:12:09.348 --> 00:12:13.312
is-A compound out there that

221
00:12:13.392 --> 00:12:15.792
was available clinically for melanoma.

222
00:12:16.192 --> 00:12:16.492
And

223
00:12:17.292 --> 00:12:20.692
so you can see that trametinib actually has a IC50 below 10

224
00:12:20.932 --> 00:12:23.092
nanomolar, so it stops these colony formations.

225
00:12:23.132 --> 00:12:25.222
So based on this data, we went into a clinical trial.

226
00:12:25.892 --> 00:12:29.772
That clinical trial was led by a very good friend of mine, Scott Szucie

227
00:12:29.892 --> 00:12:31.472
at University of Michigan.

228
00:12:32.592 --> 00:12:35.952
It was NCI.0015, and also known as SARC-33.

229
00:12:35.972 --> 00:12:39.672
It was a non-randomized, open-label, Phase 2 study of trametinib in

230
00:12:39.712 --> 00:12:43.072
patients with unresectable or metastatic EHE.

231
00:12:43.572 --> 00:12:43.742
Now,

232
00:12:44.972 --> 00:12:47.012
I'll just cut to the chase. We actually published the data.

233
00:12:47.032 --> 00:12:48.962
It's published in Clinical Cancer Research.

234
00:12:49.232 --> 00:12:50.532
We didn't meet our endpoint,

235
00:12:51.572 --> 00:12:53.092
but you can see here from this waterfall plot,

236
00:12:53.932 --> 00:12:55.672
essentially these are the non-responders here.

237
00:12:55.692 --> 00:12:58.712
We had four non-responders, but about 20 patients actually responded really well.

238
00:12:58.752 --> 00:13:02.712
The drug's relatively toxic, so one of the things was we had to take patients off

239
00:13:02.752 --> 00:13:06.112
because of the toxicity of the drug. But we actually had a great response.

240
00:13:06.292 --> 00:13:07.312
Didn't meet our endpoint, though.

241
00:13:07.352 --> 00:13:10.812
Didn't get FDA approved for this indication, but it really gave us an idea that we

242
00:13:10.832 --> 00:13:13.152
were on the right track, let me say.

243
00:13:14.452 --> 00:13:18.352
So, subsequently to doing all this sort of work with NIH3T3 cells, in

244
00:13:18.392 --> 00:13:22.132
the background, we made a genetically engineered mouse.

245
00:13:22.212 --> 00:13:23.832
This is the schemata of how we do it.

246
00:13:23.872 --> 00:13:27.432
Essentially what we did was we put in a germline allele that we could

247
00:13:27.472 --> 00:13:31.212
conditionally activate once the mice had gone through birth and were

248
00:13:31.532 --> 00:13:35.132
living, to alter it to express TAZ

249
00:13:35.212 --> 00:13:39.112
CAMTA1. So we converted, essentially, the native TAZ allele to a TAZ

250
00:13:39.172 --> 00:13:42.972
CAMTA1 allele. All the mice that had the TAZ

251
00:13:42.992 --> 00:13:44.712
CAMTA1 allele, and took two alleles, actually.

252
00:13:44.752 --> 00:13:47.652
The heterozygous TAZ CAMTA1 mice did not get EHE.

253
00:13:48.112 --> 00:13:51.792
All the homozygous mice did, and the tumors look identical to

254
00:13:51.832 --> 00:13:54.292
human EHE at any level that you looked at them.

255
00:13:54.332 --> 00:13:56.692
So they looked at them under the microscope, they looked right.

256
00:13:56.852 --> 00:13:59.532
If you did immunohistochemistry, they're a vascular tumor.

257
00:13:59.612 --> 00:13:59.972
If you did

258
00:14:01.372 --> 00:14:03.452
RNAseq, they would have the same expression profile.

259
00:14:03.492 --> 00:14:07.232
So every time we test these tumors, they are identical to human EHE.

260
00:14:09.532 --> 00:14:13.372
Then one trick we did, so CDK2A is lost in human EHE about

261
00:14:13.452 --> 00:14:16.252
half the time, and it's associated with aggressive behavior.

262
00:14:16.732 --> 00:14:19.832
We didn't get cell lines. We couldn't grow cell lines out of the original mouse

263
00:14:19.912 --> 00:14:23.832
model, so what we did was we crossed it into a CDK2A conditional background

264
00:14:23.872 --> 00:14:27.001
to make mice that were TAZ CAMTA1 homozygous,

265
00:14:27.092 --> 00:14:30.452
CDK2A homozygous. And then when we deleted

266
00:14:30.752 --> 00:14:34.312
CDK2A, activated TAZ CAMTA1, we got aggressive tumors.

267
00:14:34.732 --> 00:14:37.052
But nicely, those tumors were able to grow into cell lines.

268
00:14:37.082 --> 00:14:40.492
And we've actually replicated this now using RB1 and some other tumor

269
00:14:40.552 --> 00:14:42.892
suppressors. And you get the same effect each time.

270
00:14:42.932 --> 00:14:45.352
The tumors are more aggressive, and you can make cell lines.

271
00:14:45.372 --> 00:14:49.352
So we have this little library now of EHE mouse cell lines that we've made

272
00:14:49.372 --> 00:14:51.112
with sort of different genetic backgrounds.

273
00:14:52.752 --> 00:14:56.312
So we used those cells then to look to see, does trametinib inhibit them?

274
00:14:56.352 --> 00:14:57.792
And of course they do, and you can see here.

275
00:14:57.812 --> 00:15:00.941
Here's three different cell lines, 36, 317, and 3.26.

276
00:15:01.252 --> 00:15:03.742
They're all inhibited. They have nice IC50s.

277
00:15:04.312 --> 00:15:08.032
And then what we were interested in then was, could we combine that with TEAD?

278
00:15:08.552 --> 00:15:11.852
And so there is a tool compound out there called MGH CP1,

279
00:15:12.912 --> 00:15:15.712
made by Dr. Wu at Mass General. And

280
00:15:18.412 --> 00:15:21.692
so TEAD inhibitors also work quite nicely. Now this is a tool compound.

281
00:15:21.732 --> 00:15:25.252
It's active at millimolar concentrations, and so not something that's going to move

282
00:15:25.272 --> 00:15:29.192
into the clinic. However, it does inhibit the growth of these

283
00:15:29.232 --> 00:15:30.441
EHE cell lines,

284
00:15:31.532 --> 00:15:33.332
and it also inhibits

285
00:15:34.652 --> 00:15:36.792
a reporter construct as well.

286
00:15:38.452 --> 00:15:41.332
And so then when you actually combine mechanists now with

287
00:15:41.392 --> 00:15:45.012
trametinib, with

288
00:15:46.492 --> 00:15:50.152
this TEAD inhibitor, you can see it has a synergistic effect as sort of

289
00:15:50.212 --> 00:15:54.122
indicated here with this big hump in this plot here on

290
00:15:54.152 --> 00:15:58.072
the right side. And so, these two synergize together, and we

291
00:15:58.112 --> 00:16:01.732
imagine that TEAD inhibitors will eventually need to be combined with a bunch of

292
00:16:01.772 --> 00:16:04.832
other and different kinds of inhibitors to move into the clinic.

293
00:16:06.272 --> 00:16:10.182
Okay, so what else have we done? So once we got these cell lines, another thing we

294
00:16:10.192 --> 00:16:13.452
did was we developed an assay to screen drug libraries.

295
00:16:13.852 --> 00:16:17.592
And what we're interested in doing is looking for abrogation, essentially, of

296
00:16:17.652 --> 00:16:20.912
TC expression, or removal from the nucleus, causing it to

297
00:16:20.952 --> 00:16:24.922
be obliterated or whatever. And so you can see here, this is the way we set up

298
00:16:24.972 --> 00:16:28.791
the assay. Here's TC in our cell line. Here's a blocking peptide.

299
00:16:28.952 --> 00:16:31.112
We did the same thing with YAP and CAMTA1.

300
00:16:31.152 --> 00:16:34.892
So we had different markers that we could use in this screen, and we set up a

301
00:16:35.252 --> 00:16:39.242
384-well plate. We first looked at a bunch of inhibitors that

302
00:16:39.252 --> 00:16:40.942
were thought to inhibit the Hippo pathway.

303
00:16:41.462 --> 00:16:44.432
I didn't get into this, but Hippo pathway tries to

304
00:16:45.872 --> 00:16:49.632
regulate the localization of TAZ CAMTA1, but it is unable to do so.

305
00:16:49.732 --> 00:16:53.212
So TAZ CAMTA1 lives constitutively in the nucleus in

306
00:16:53.272 --> 00:16:57.092
EHE, and in fact, none of these compounds worked.

307
00:16:57.572 --> 00:16:59.552
Osmotic stress is the only thing that had any effect.

308
00:16:59.952 --> 00:17:03.212
Sodium chloride at 200 millimolar, which essentially just blows the cells up

309
00:17:03.972 --> 00:17:04.772
to a large degree.

310
00:17:05.833 --> 00:17:09.093
Now looking at our screen, we started with these custom libraries that we have in

311
00:17:09.113 --> 00:17:12.192
our medicinal chemistry group. We had about 4,000 compounds.

312
00:17:13.312 --> 00:17:16.792
Just looking at things that had an increased cytoplasmic-to-nuclear ratio or

313
00:17:16.912 --> 00:17:19.652
disappearance, essentially, of the nuclear signal, we had 38 hits.

314
00:17:20.452 --> 00:17:24.272
Seven of them were active at one micromolar, and then we had clear dose responses

315
00:17:24.312 --> 00:17:27.992
in five compounds. The five compounds are listed over here on the right.

316
00:17:28.333 --> 00:17:32.232
So we have dinaciclib and CGP, which are both cyclin-dependent

317
00:17:32.272 --> 00:17:34.832
kinase inhibitors. We have DBET6, which is a

318
00:17:34.872 --> 00:17:38.802
bromodomain-containing protein, and a lot of people are interested

319
00:17:38.812 --> 00:17:40.132
in BRD4 inhibition.

320
00:17:41.012 --> 00:17:42.432
And then XPB.

321
00:17:44.212 --> 00:17:47.872
Here's just a couple dose response curves looking at CGP.

322
00:17:47.972 --> 00:17:51.952
So you can see it has a nice dose response curve, the same with dinaciclib, another

323
00:17:51.992 --> 00:17:53.032
CDK inhibitor.

324
00:17:55.412 --> 00:17:58.912
We did get at apoptosis with these compounds, and so,

325
00:17:59.792 --> 00:18:00.112
again,

326
00:18:01.132 --> 00:18:05.092
looking at CGP and dina, they both increased apoptosis to quite a

327
00:18:05.492 --> 00:18:08.452
degree, which kind of surprised us, because usually these single inhibitors don't

328
00:18:08.492 --> 00:18:08.931
do that.

329
00:18:09.912 --> 00:18:12.736
Sorry.We did an in vivo study here.

330
00:18:12.756 --> 00:18:15.736
So we're looking at, this is a xenograft mouse.

331
00:18:15.776 --> 00:18:19.456
So our cell lines that we've created out of our genetically engineered model also

332
00:18:19.476 --> 00:18:22.276
grow as xenografts. We can inject them into the flanks of these mice.

333
00:18:22.676 --> 00:18:23.196
Here's actually

334
00:18:24.276 --> 00:18:27.396
vascular invasion. There's a little clump of tumor traveling off.

335
00:18:27.436 --> 00:18:27.886
And so these

336
00:18:29.096 --> 00:18:32.276
cell lines actually metastasize at very high rates, which is kind of unusual.

337
00:18:32.676 --> 00:18:36.016
Here you can see the lung of an untreated mouse, virtually completely replaced by

338
00:18:36.056 --> 00:18:39.286
cancer. And then over on the right side, you can see after dinacyclin treatment.

339
00:18:39.296 --> 00:18:40.316
So there was actually a really big

340
00:18:41.336 --> 00:18:43.816
reduction in the amount of tumor

341
00:18:44.856 --> 00:18:46.516
mass essentially in these lungs.

342
00:18:48.576 --> 00:18:51.216
We looked to see which CDK's inhibitors

343
00:18:52.096 --> 00:18:55.836
work, because a lot of these inhibitors inhibit more than one CDK.

344
00:18:56.396 --> 00:18:59.816
And so it turned out dinacyclin inhibited this group over here

345
00:18:59.856 --> 00:19:02.936
of cell cycle regulated and transcriptional.

346
00:19:04.316 --> 00:19:08.296
And it turned out essentially, I'll just summarize, that CDK9 appears

347
00:19:08.336 --> 00:19:10.416
to be the target of this.

348
00:19:11.376 --> 00:19:11.696
And then our

349
00:19:12.556 --> 00:19:15.076
current hypothesis is that a lot of the

350
00:19:15.896 --> 00:19:19.216
compounds that were actually successful, so these ones over here on the left, all

351
00:19:19.276 --> 00:19:22.386
turn out to target things that are part of this productive elongation complex.

352
00:19:22.456 --> 00:19:25.976
It's involved in transcription. And so we think somehow that CDK9

353
00:19:25.986 --> 00:19:29.386
inhibition blows apart the complex, and we have some data that

354
00:19:29.856 --> 00:19:33.776
supports that now, and we're trying to develop that as a full story, but that

355
00:19:33.796 --> 00:19:37.136
hasn't been published. This particular data's unpublished at this point, although

356
00:19:37.156 --> 00:19:40.756
we published a lot of the CDK9 story a couple years ago in Clinical

357
00:19:40.856 --> 00:19:41.696
Cancer Research.

358
00:19:42.876 --> 00:19:45.306
And then I just want to talk about the last thing that we're really working on in

359
00:19:45.336 --> 00:19:46.616
the lab right now, which is

360
00:19:47.956 --> 00:19:51.276
we're trying to actually identify or develop an inhibitor

361
00:19:51.516 --> 00:19:55.416
of TEAD, and we have an NCI Next program that I work

362
00:19:55.436 --> 00:19:59.376
with a bunch of medicinal chemists, namely Sean Stauffer and Bin Zhou, who are

363
00:19:59.436 --> 00:20:03.286
at the Cleveland Clinic. And so this is the structure actually of TEAD, and it's

364
00:20:03.316 --> 00:20:05.986
got this central binding pocket, and then it's got these

365
00:20:07.076 --> 00:20:09.166
external interfaces that are all drugable.

366
00:20:10.796 --> 00:20:12.656
And so here's interface one, two, and three.

367
00:20:12.756 --> 00:20:14.706
We are interested in drugging

368
00:20:15.796 --> 00:20:18.246
interface three. These are where Yap and Taz would bind.

369
00:20:21.776 --> 00:20:25.386
Here you can see actually dramatically, Yap, Taz, and something called Vestigial 2,

370
00:20:25.456 --> 00:20:28.395
they all bind to these interfaces over here.

371
00:20:28.636 --> 00:20:32.476
You've got Vestigial 1, 3, and 4 over here, and then PHAM proteins.

372
00:20:32.656 --> 00:20:35.585
They all bind to different parts of TEAD, whether they're co-activators,

373
00:20:35.656 --> 00:20:39.455
co-repressors, or unknown regulator function.

374
00:20:39.836 --> 00:20:42.216
And so the idea here is to develop molecules.

375
00:20:42.376 --> 00:20:45.796
So these are actually the binding sites for Yap and Taz, one of the

376
00:20:45.816 --> 00:20:49.676
interfaces. And you can see that these pockets are occupied by different

377
00:20:49.956 --> 00:20:51.196
parts of Yap and Taz.

378
00:20:52.716 --> 00:20:54.796
Here's Yap over here and here's Vestigial 2.

379
00:20:55.176 --> 00:20:58.716
And so the idea is to develop an inhibitor, a small molecule which sits in these

380
00:20:58.796 --> 00:21:01.316
pockets and inhibits the binding.

381
00:21:03.236 --> 00:21:06.776
And the way that we started doing this was, well, we tried a few

382
00:21:06.836 --> 00:21:10.436
approaches, but the thing that worked the best was NMR peptide screening.

383
00:21:10.496 --> 00:21:14.276
So you can get peptide libraries and then screen by NMR with the

384
00:21:14.316 --> 00:21:16.495
interaction of these peptides with the

385
00:21:17.476 --> 00:21:21.376
protein that you're studying. Here's the device that we use, and I

386
00:21:21.396 --> 00:21:23.456
don't know much about that, so I'm not going to talk about it.

387
00:21:23.976 --> 00:21:24.166
But

388
00:21:25.116 --> 00:21:27.826
this would be the pipeline for how you develop this.

389
00:21:27.856 --> 00:21:31.496
So the first thing is you get hits, then you do structure-based design, which is

390
00:21:31.516 --> 00:21:33.676
where we still are largely in our study.

391
00:21:34.016 --> 00:21:36.176
And I'm not going to talk a ton about it, but just a little bit.

392
00:21:36.576 --> 00:21:38.176
But this is kind of what the data looks like.

393
00:21:38.196 --> 00:21:41.756
For those of you who aren't used to looking at NMR data, probably one of the

394
00:21:41.796 --> 00:21:45.136
funnest things I've done in my career is to hook up with these chemists a few years

395
00:21:45.176 --> 00:21:48.636
ago and learn a lot of chemistry that kind of remembered a little bit from being an

