entered the ENCODE pipeline. And it had this

704
00:38:56.164 --> 00:38:59.144
incredible signal here, but all the other ENCODE cell lines that had been

705
00:38:59.804 --> 00:39:02.844
profiled didn't have any activity on microsatellite repeats.

706
00:39:03.274 --> 00:39:05.184
And importantly, if you think about

707
00:39:06.184 --> 00:39:10.064
this collection of cell lines, many of them have the wild-type FLI1

708
00:39:10.084 --> 00:39:12.304
transcription factor expressed at very high levels.

709
00:39:12.684 --> 00:39:16.624
There's many of the lineages that are represented have FLI1, and yet

710
00:39:16.644 --> 00:39:19.484
they don't have the microsatellite repeat activation.

711
00:39:20.084 --> 00:39:23.024
So this prompted a simple experiment, which was to

712
00:39:23.844 --> 00:39:27.584
go into a mesenchymal stem cell model and introduce EWS FLI1

713
00:39:27.624 --> 00:39:30.244
versus the wild-type FLI1 transcription factor.

714
00:39:30.284 --> 00:39:33.784
And if you do this experiment, it's actually a very clear result.

715
00:39:33.824 --> 00:39:36.434
EWS FLI1 binds microsatellite repeats,

716
00:39:37.244 --> 00:39:40.544
whereas FLI1 does not or kind of tries to bind.

717
00:39:40.564 --> 00:39:44.544
You have a little bit of signal here, but not really a stabilization of the

718
00:39:44.584 --> 00:39:45.054
complex.

719
00:39:46.604 --> 00:39:50.474
The fusion protein actually opens chromatin beautifully, FLI1

720
00:39:50.504 --> 00:39:54.344
does not on these microsatellite repeats, and it activates chromatin beautifully on

721
00:39:54.424 --> 00:39:56.584
microsatellite repeats, but FLI1 does not.

722
00:39:56.604 --> 00:40:00.164
So for us, it's very exciting because you're talking about something that's

723
00:40:00.224 --> 00:40:04.084
fundamentally different about the oncogenic version of a transcription

724
00:40:04.184 --> 00:40:06.864
factor compared to the wild-type version of a transcription factor.

725
00:40:07.344 --> 00:40:10.744
So looking at other EWS fusions, we have found the same theme.

726
00:40:10.804 --> 00:40:14.374
So in clear cell sarcoma, EWS ATF1 and DSRCT, EWS

727
00:40:14.424 --> 00:40:18.044
OT1 have similar patterns of unusual

728
00:40:18.124 --> 00:40:21.664
transcription factor binding sites, often loosely repetitive, not necessarily

729
00:40:21.984 --> 00:40:25.924
perfect microsatellites, where they like to bind and where

730
00:40:26.064 --> 00:40:29.304
the corresponding wild-type transcription factor never goes.

731
00:40:29.384 --> 00:40:33.304
So we think that one of the themes of these fusions is that they

732
00:40:33.384 --> 00:40:37.104
are pioneer factors in different parts of the genome compared to the

733
00:40:37.124 --> 00:40:38.224
wild-type transcription factor.

734
00:40:39.324 --> 00:40:43.164
So what else do they do? I will quickly go through this. This is already published.

735
00:40:43.524 --> 00:40:47.084
They make loops, of course. When these things bind, they form

736
00:40:47.104 --> 00:40:51.004
enhancer-like structures that have this concentration of the fusion protein, and

737
00:40:51.044 --> 00:40:54.484
they nicely loop. And in fact, they are dominant in terms of the looping structure

738
00:40:54.524 --> 00:40:56.184
in the genome. This is from EWS FLI1.

739
00:40:56.644 --> 00:40:59.544
The loops made by EWS FLI1 binding are enormous by Hi-C.

740
00:41:00.624 --> 00:41:04.564
The loops here shown in blue are actually the loops that do not involve

741
00:41:04.584 --> 00:41:08.464
EWS FLI1 in this cell. So it's a huge difference in terms of the ability

742
00:41:08.504 --> 00:41:12.184
to change this 3D configuration of the

743
00:41:12.224 --> 00:41:15.764
genome. And we felt that it was

744
00:41:15.784 --> 00:41:19.564
important to prove that these strange binding sites, these

745
00:41:19.624 --> 00:41:23.444
microsatellite repeats, were actually important for the disease because it could

746
00:41:23.464 --> 00:41:26.784
have been an epiphenomenon. It could be a sticky protein and somehow you bind.

747
00:41:27.204 --> 00:41:30.924
So the way that we answered this question was to create an

748
00:41:30.964 --> 00:41:34.684
artificial zinc finger transcription factor that can only

749
00:41:34.704 --> 00:41:38.084
bind GGAA repeats, and we did this in collaboration with Keith Joung's lab, who's

750
00:41:38.104 --> 00:41:40.984
an expert in zinc fingers. We tried to do this experiment by CRISPR initially.

751
00:41:41.004 --> 00:41:44.864
It doesn't work. It's actually very hard to have a CRISPR attach

752
00:41:44.924 --> 00:41:48.744
specifically at microsatellite repeats because the protein is very

753
00:41:48.804 --> 00:41:52.084
large, and the spacing is difficult, and in fact, it's very hard to have CRISPRs

754
00:41:52.164 --> 00:41:53.764
bind thousands of sites in the genome.

755
00:41:54.204 --> 00:41:58.064
If you make an artificial zinc finger, you can actually design it such

756
00:41:58.184 --> 00:42:00.164
that it only binds microsatellite repeats.

757
00:42:00.224 --> 00:42:04.184
So we can actually replicate the transcriptional signature of

758
00:42:04.204 --> 00:42:07.924
Ewing sarcoma by adding an EWS zinc finger, which was our positive

759
00:42:07.964 --> 00:42:10.304
control. We can do this, and it binds very nicely.

760
00:42:10.364 --> 00:42:14.004
It doesn't bind to the single GGAA sites, only to the repetitive ones.

761
00:42:14.784 --> 00:42:17.784
And in fact, it activates chromatin very well.

762
00:42:17.804 --> 00:42:21.364
But most importantly, when we actually switch off the

763
00:42:21.444 --> 00:42:24.844
activating part of the zinc finger to a Krab domain, repressive domain,

764
00:42:25.364 --> 00:42:29.304
we actually can silence all the microsatellite repeats and not the GGAA binding

765
00:42:29.364 --> 00:42:32.664
sites in the genome. So it's a very specific genetic trick that we're using.

766
00:42:32.704 --> 00:42:36.324
We turn off all the microsatellite repeats, and lo and behold, what we see is that

767
00:42:36.344 --> 00:42:40.224
Ewing sarcoma cell lines completely collapse, whereas other types

768
00:42:40.264 --> 00:42:42.524
of cells are fine with this massive

769
00:42:43.484 --> 00:42:46.144
silencing of the genome that we actually have induced.

770
00:42:46.164 --> 00:42:49.764
But it's the Ewing sarcoma cells that are exquisitely sensitive to the

771
00:42:49.804 --> 00:42:53.452
microsatellite activity.So,

772
00:42:54.672 --> 00:42:58.512
why is all of this happening? Why is the transcription factor in this

773
00:42:58.532 --> 00:43:01.592
oncogenic form being able to go to a different part of the genome?

774
00:43:01.832 --> 00:43:05.472
So obviously the answer, now going back to genetics, was always about

775
00:43:05.512 --> 00:43:09.112
EWS, right? So if you have the weird addition of a

776
00:43:09.151 --> 00:43:12.312
disordered domain, there's always a disordered domain of a FET protein.

777
00:43:12.492 --> 00:43:14.792
So a transcription factor, is that doing something new?

778
00:43:15.172 --> 00:43:18.892
So it turns out that EWS and FET proteins have a different

779
00:43:18.912 --> 00:43:22.712
life in science, in neurodegeneration, because they have been linked

780
00:43:23.012 --> 00:43:26.712
to an abnormal aggregation in neurodegenerative diseases.

781
00:43:26.752 --> 00:43:30.292
And there's a number of papers particularly linking fuse and now

782
00:43:30.352 --> 00:43:34.232
TAF15 as well to the neurodegenerative diseases like ALS and others.

783
00:43:34.752 --> 00:43:38.492
And in fact, there's been some really exciting papers

784
00:43:39.072 --> 00:43:42.892
published that show that you can actually model

785
00:43:42.932 --> 00:43:46.332
this pretty well in a number of different assays,

786
00:43:46.952 --> 00:43:50.652
and this is an interesting picture from a paper

787
00:43:50.752 --> 00:43:54.732
from the McKnight Lab in UT Southwestern, showing that

788
00:43:54.772 --> 00:43:58.732
these things make gel-like globs of protein when you actually

789
00:43:58.792 --> 00:44:00.932
can purify, which is really hard to purify, by the way,

790
00:44:01.812 --> 00:44:05.472
but they also precipitate very quickly out of

791
00:44:05.552 --> 00:44:08.892
solution. So we were able to show that many of these properties, and

792
00:44:08.972 --> 00:44:12.812
actually not surprisingly, are maintained by the EWS-FLI1

793
00:44:12.872 --> 00:44:15.812
version of this that contains this EWS disordered domain.

794
00:44:16.852 --> 00:44:20.842
So we went back to our model system in mesenchymal stem cells, and

795
00:44:20.872 --> 00:44:21.292
we can ask

796
00:44:22.132 --> 00:44:26.012
the question now, what if we disrupt the disordered properties of

797
00:44:26.052 --> 00:44:29.812
the EWS domain? And to do this, we just borrowed a number of mutants that have been

798
00:44:29.832 --> 00:44:33.812
described in the neurodegeneration literature that abrogate the phase

799
00:44:33.872 --> 00:44:35.812
transition properties of the disordered domain.

800
00:44:35.892 --> 00:44:37.832
So we borrowed these mutants, which are not a single

801
00:44:38.972 --> 00:44:42.212
amino acid mutant, but a series of amino acids that change a number of the

802
00:44:42.232 --> 00:44:43.672
tyrosines in the disordered domain.

803
00:44:44.132 --> 00:44:47.852
And when you make this and you lose the ability to

804
00:44:47.952 --> 00:44:51.872
undergo phase transitions, you actually lose the activity of turning

805
00:44:51.892 --> 00:44:54.132
on enhancers. So we actually need the activity for

806
00:44:55.132 --> 00:44:58.932
turning on enhancers. But most importantly, we also made a number of

807
00:44:58.992 --> 00:45:02.712
mutants that attached small pieces

808
00:45:03.071 --> 00:45:06.312
of the EWS disordered domain to FLI1.

809
00:45:06.641 --> 00:45:10.372
And these are non-contiguous small pieces of about 80 amino acids.

810
00:45:10.792 --> 00:45:14.671
And you can get any of those pieces attached to FLI1, and you recapitulate the

811
00:45:14.692 --> 00:45:18.682
ability of a fusion to turn on all the microsatellite

812
00:45:18.712 --> 00:45:22.552
repeats and turn on all the genes that we're familiar with in Ewing sarcoma.

813
00:45:23.112 --> 00:45:26.891
So really, we feel that this makes a very strong point that the

814
00:45:26.932 --> 00:45:30.752
properties of the disordered domain of EWS are really responsible for this

815
00:45:30.832 --> 00:45:34.612
ability to change the binding properties of

816
00:45:34.672 --> 00:45:37.951
the transcription factor and bind to microsatellite repeats.

817
00:45:38.012 --> 00:45:40.852
So now this is something that has

818
00:45:40.912 --> 00:45:44.701
become an interesting area of biology.

819
00:45:45.352 --> 00:45:49.252
I think one of the examples that brought this forth was the

820
00:45:49.312 --> 00:45:50.532
work on EWS fusions

821
00:45:51.352 --> 00:45:52.312
by our lab and others.

822
00:45:53.232 --> 00:45:55.912
And let me just show you that

823
00:45:56.952 --> 00:45:58.992
when you express

824
00:46:00.052 --> 00:46:04.032
the IDR of a FET protein with an mCherry, you

825
00:46:04.052 --> 00:46:05.672
actually form these condensates.

826
00:46:05.892 --> 00:46:09.792
And condensates are a term that has become very prominent in the

827
00:46:09.832 --> 00:46:13.512
literature. There's still some problems with the definition, but clearly, if you do

828
00:46:13.532 --> 00:46:17.072
the experiment, you form these kind of lava lamp

829
00:46:17.152 --> 00:46:20.872
like aggregates of protein. So these proteins

830
00:46:20.912 --> 00:46:24.292
really like to come together. That might be an explanation for why

831
00:46:24.352 --> 00:46:27.972
they are very good at binding microsatellites, because they stabilize the

832
00:46:28.012 --> 00:46:31.772
proteins in those locations. But there's also an important point to be

833
00:46:31.782 --> 00:46:35.582
made here. This is just the disordered domain by itself,

834
00:46:35.972 --> 00:46:39.602
which eventually, once you start forming, with epigenetics you can stimulate

835
00:46:39.602 --> 00:46:43.492
this, you start forming the condensates, they eventually just glob onto

836
00:46:43.592 --> 00:46:46.132
each other and just become a single dot, right?

837
00:46:46.832 --> 00:46:50.452
If you have attachment to the DNA, like what we

838
00:46:50.492 --> 00:46:51.632
see in the

839
00:46:52.712 --> 00:46:56.472
case of the tumors, and this is actually a construct made by Sacha Xiong

840
00:46:57.432 --> 00:47:01.412
in Robert Tjian's lab, which actually has a Halo tag attached to the

841
00:47:01.432 --> 00:47:05.112
fusion endogenously. What you see in this type

842
00:47:05.172 --> 00:47:08.992
of assay is actually that these things don't stick to each

843
00:47:09.052 --> 00:47:10.542
other. They just stay attached to the chromosome.

844
00:47:10.582 --> 00:47:14.372
So the interaction with the DNA keeps the condensates from totally going

845
00:47:14.472 --> 00:47:18.132
awry and actually keeps them in a functional configuration where they can still

846
00:47:18.212 --> 00:47:21.732
activate the enhancers. So there's an interesting balance there that could be

847
00:47:21.772 --> 00:47:25.332
something to think about in terms of how this system is maintained.

848
00:47:25.832 --> 00:47:29.552
And importantly, Sacha was able to show very nicely that

849
00:47:30.112 --> 00:47:33.392
the sites where we find microsatellites are actually surrounded by

850
00:47:33.512 --> 00:47:37.472
clouds of deposition of EWS

851
00:47:38.252 --> 00:47:41.612
and FET proteins that you can actually track on the

852
00:47:41.632 --> 00:47:45.612
nucleosomes. So are these condensates, do they have all the properties

853
00:47:45.632 --> 00:47:49.512
of condensates? That is actually very hard to do because condensates, as we

854
00:47:49.552 --> 00:47:52.712
understand them, are often defined by

855
00:47:52.752 --> 00:47:54.372
analogy or to

856
00:47:55.712 --> 00:47:57.952
membrane-less organelles like the nucleolus.

857
00:47:58.392 --> 00:48:00.792
So there's a number of properties that you can study at that scale.

858
00:48:01.172 --> 00:48:02.772
These are enhancer size condensates.

859
00:48:02.812 --> 00:48:06.432
They're really small, and some of the things that you would like to do in

860
00:48:06.752 --> 00:48:10.072
terms of testing their properties actually stretch the limits of some of the

861
00:48:10.092 --> 00:48:11.152
microscopy techniques.

862
00:48:12.652 --> 00:48:12.952
So,

863
00:48:14.052 --> 00:48:17.572
the model then is that once you have

864
00:48:17.712 --> 00:48:21.372
a transcription factor that's fused to an EWS domain,

865
00:48:21.772 --> 00:48:25.432
you have the ability to bind different parts of the genome, and that is going to

866
00:48:25.492 --> 00:48:29.312
let you activate new sites. So for us, this

867
00:48:29.372 --> 00:48:31.872
brought forth the disordered domain

868
00:48:33.352 --> 00:48:37.112
as a really important aspect of the biology of these fusions that really needs to

869
00:48:37.132 --> 00:48:40.888
be studied and that we need to understand better.So we saw, and this is

870
00:48:40.928 --> 00:48:41.928
where some of the

871
00:48:43.308 --> 00:48:47.188
amazing insights that come from studying rare diseases can guide

872
00:48:47.228 --> 00:48:49.468
you into interesting parts of biology.

873
00:48:49.548 --> 00:48:51.048
I think it has happened over and over

874
00:48:51.888 --> 00:48:55.788
in molecular biology, for sure. And for us, it just made us

875
00:48:55.808 --> 00:48:59.368
ask the question, can we look at how disordered domains arrange themselves in the

876
00:48:59.468 --> 00:49:03.328
nucleus? So we came up with an idea that actually was based on an

877
00:49:03.348 --> 00:49:04.888
experiment done by Steve McKnight,

878
00:49:05.928 --> 00:49:09.518
which was using a chemical precipitant of disordered

879
00:49:09.608 --> 00:49:11.488
proteins to try to map them in the genome.

880
00:49:11.588 --> 00:49:14.748
So what the McKnight lab had done was found that there's a

881
00:49:15.788 --> 00:49:19.718
chemical called beta-isox that has the ability to precipitate disordered

882
00:49:19.718 --> 00:49:23.588
proteins. Why is that? It's because it creates microcrystals, and

883
00:49:23.648 --> 00:49:27.038
those crystals then are able to interact with

884
00:49:27.868 --> 00:49:30.448
polypeptide chains that are not globular.

885
00:49:30.638 --> 00:49:31.848
A globular chain does not

886
00:49:32.708 --> 00:49:36.578
interact with a microcrystal, but a chain that is loose will interact and

887
00:49:36.608 --> 00:49:40.168
will precipitate. And this has been used in a number of biochemical

888
00:49:40.178 --> 00:49:44.148
assays that we had used in terms of Western blotting or whatnot.

889
00:49:44.168 --> 00:49:48.148
But we had the idea, well, if we're doing this, why don't we collect all the DNA

890
00:49:48.188 --> 00:49:50.728
that comes down with the precipitates and map it back to the genome?

891
00:49:51.448 --> 00:49:55.428
So if you do that in a technique that we call DiF-seq, we were surprised that

892
00:49:55.508 --> 00:49:58.428
you get actually something that looks very much like ChIP-seq without any

893
00:49:58.448 --> 00:50:02.248
antibodies. So you can actually look at where is there a big concentration of

894
00:50:02.288 --> 00:50:03.498
disordered proteins in the genome.

895
00:50:03.878 --> 00:50:06.788
And here's a peak right where Eos fly one is sitting.

896
00:50:06.828 --> 00:50:10.758
You have this whole blob of disordered proteins that is sitting there, and

897
00:50:10.828 --> 00:50:14.168
notice how much bigger it is than the binding site of the transcription factors.

898
00:50:14.248 --> 00:50:15.988
There's a number of other things that are here.

899
00:50:17.448 --> 00:50:21.268
Importantly, it's not just where the fusion is, is a Ewing sarcoma, but also there

900
00:50:21.308 --> 00:50:23.648
are a number of places where there's no fusion and also there's

901
00:50:24.208 --> 00:50:28.168
aggregations of disordered proteins that we have no idea what

902
00:50:28.188 --> 00:50:32.148
they are. So we did some analysis of this, and of course, we

903
00:50:32.188 --> 00:50:35.048
can find it in different parts of the genome, in activated places.

904
00:50:35.328 --> 00:50:39.168
Interestingly, weak enhancers have actually more signals for disordered

905
00:50:39.178 --> 00:50:42.508
proteins than active enhancers. So this doesn't match, for example,

906
00:50:43.028 --> 00:50:46.668
with cadence and acetyl perfectly, doesn't match with, I would say, even

907
00:50:46.708 --> 00:50:50.588
ATAC-seq exactly because we find places that are closed chromatin that have

908
00:50:50.648 --> 00:50:52.568
disordered domains attached to them.

909
00:50:52.668 --> 00:50:56.488
And in fact, this kind of analysis, the only analysis that will

910
00:50:56.528 --> 00:50:59.128
show you that there are proteins, this is a large enhancer.

911
00:50:59.658 --> 00:51:03.048
There's protein signals in places of enhancers that we wouldn't know belong to the

912
00:51:03.088 --> 00:51:06.488
enhancer if we were looking at cadence and acetyl, and we wouldn't know if they're

913
00:51:06.498 --> 00:51:10.328
part of bound sites if you look at ATAC-seq, but actually probably

914
00:51:10.368 --> 00:51:13.628
form an interesting architecture that we're not aware of at this point.

915
00:51:15.388 --> 00:51:19.208
So you can actually map what domains are binding to the sites, and we can find some

916
00:51:19.228 --> 00:51:23.148
transcription factors that actually are represented in some of

917
00:51:23.188 --> 00:51:26.508
the sites that we've identified. We can also

918
00:51:27.068 --> 00:51:31.028
do experiments where we repeat this assay after turning off the Eos fly

919
00:51:31.088 --> 00:51:34.908
one fusion, for example. And interestingly there, what we found is that we

920
00:51:34.948 --> 00:51:38.148
see a big increase in signals after we turn off Eos fly one.

921
00:51:38.268 --> 00:51:41.828
All the Eos fly one sites disappear, but there's a number of

922
00:51:41.868 --> 00:51:45.607
sites that appear. So this brought us to an interesting

923
00:51:45.648 --> 00:51:49.558
realization, which is that if you look at these very large DiF-seq domains,

924
00:51:49.628 --> 00:51:52.638
very often you have other transcription factors, not just Eos fly one, that are

925
00:51:52.708 --> 00:51:54.888
attached to these locations. Okay?

926
00:51:55.328 --> 00:51:58.928
But when you actually turn off the fusion,

927
00:51:59.328 --> 00:52:03.188
this whole complex and this whole very large size, this is about

928
00:52:03.268 --> 00:52:07.198
five KBs in size. This whole thing just disappears,

929
00:52:07.428 --> 00:52:10.797
and it releases a number of proteins with disordered domains that are sitting in

930
00:52:10.828 --> 00:52:14.568
this location. One of them is a transcription factor that we were able to map,

931
00:52:14.708 --> 00:52:17.668
NFIB, that then goes on and sits somewhere else in the genome.

932
00:52:18.088 --> 00:52:21.888
So the fusion proteins are not only able to open new

933
00:52:21.948 --> 00:52:25.688
parts of the genome and activate it, but also are attracting a lot of

934
00:52:25.768 --> 00:52:29.548
disordered proteins and procreating a situation where you have

935
00:52:29.588 --> 00:52:32.248
sequestration of disordered proteins in an abnormal way.

936
